  "exercises": [
    {
      "id": "pyramid-of-psychological-needs",
      "name": "Pyramid of Psychological Needs",
      "instructions": "Arrange your cards into a three-tiered pyramid representing your psychological needs, inspired by Maslow's hierarchy.\n\n1. **Love and Belonging** (bottom row): Choose three or four cards from the LOVE, FAMILY or FRIENDSHIP/SOCIABILITY categories \u2014 those that relate to your intimate relationships, friendships, family, colleagues or romantic partners.\n\n2. **Esteem** (middle row): Choose two to three cards from the WORK, MONEY, MOOD or BODY categories \u2014 those that relate to your need for esteem, gaining prestige, and feeling a sense of accomplishment.\n\n3. **Self-Actualisation** (top row): Choose one or two cards from the SELF, LEISURE and MEANING categories \u2014 those that support your need for self-actualisation, achieving your full potential and fulfilling your life's purpose.",
      "groups": [
        "Love and Belonging",
        "Esteem",
        "Self-Actualisation"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "priority-planner",
      "name": "Priority Planner",
      "instructions": "Our goals and priorities require differing amounts of effort and different timeframes to achieve. Some are short term; others can only be accomplished over a much longer period.\n\nOnce you've selected a number of goals and priorities you wish to work towards, sort them according to the time you expect it will take to achieve them. Use this planner as a guide to tackle your goals, and a reminder of the time it will take to achieve your most treasured ambitions.",
      "groups": [
        "This Week",
        "This Month",
        "This Year",
        "Within Five Years",
        "Over a Lifetime"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "tournament-of-priorities",
      "name": "Tournament of Priorities",
      "instructions": "It is often hard to decide where to focus when we can identify many areas we'd like to improve. This exercise helps you decide which of your goals matters most.\n\nStage a tournament of priorities. First, choose 8\u201310 possible goals and priorities from a particular category you feel you would like to work towards. Then sort them into pairs and pit them against each other, eliminating whichever one you feel you could live without achieving. Advance from the quarter-finals to the semi-finals and then on to the final itself.\n\nYou should arrive at a single champion goal: the one you are most invested in meeting. At the same time, you'll be left with a number of close runners-up to tackle once your champion has been achieved.",
      "groups": [
        "Quarter-Finals",
        "Semi-Finals",
        "Final",
        "Champion"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "steps-to-fulfilment",
      "name": "Steps to Fulfilment",
      "instructions": "A common pitfall when setting goals is over-ambition. We set our sights on a lofty target and fall into despair when it appears beyond our capabilities. The solution is not to give up, but to refocus on smaller, more achievable goals that will help us take steps towards attaining the ultimate one.\n\nFirst, select an ultimate goal from a particular category \u2014 an ambitious target you would like to reach but are currently some way off from achieving. Next, search through the deck and select any other goal or priority that will help you move towards this ultimate goal \u2014 ones that will give you the necessary skills, means, opportunities and experiences to progress.\n\nArrange your chosen cards into a set of discrete, sequential steps \u2014 an achievable programme where you can feel pride and progress with every step you take.",
      "groups": [
        "Step 1",
        "Step 2",
        "Step 3",
        "Step 4",
        "Step 5",
        "Ultimate Goal"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "feasibility-fulfilment-matrix",
      "name": "The Feasibility-Fulfilment Matrix",
      "instructions": "Our goals can be measured on two axes: feasibility and fulfilment. This exercise helps you plot your goals on both axes as a way of deciding which to prioritise.\n\nMake a selection of 10 or so cards, either from a single category or a sample from different categories you wish to focus on. Place each card into one of four quadrants:\n\n1. **Inessentials** \u2014 not very feasible and only somewhat fulfilling. Probably not worth your time and effort.\n2. **Nice to Haves** \u2014 highly feasible but only somewhat fulfilling. They shouldn't demand your full focus, but may still be worth attempting.\n3. **Distant Dreams** \u2014 not very feasible but highly fulfilling. Worth aiming for, but the scale of the challenge should be kept in mind.\n4. **Achievable Ambitions** \u2014 very feasible and highly fulfilling. These should be your highest priority: they offer the most guaranteed route to fulfilment.",
      "groups": [
        "Inessentials",
        "Nice to Haves",
        "Distant Dreams",
        "Achievable Ambitions"
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "wallet-nightstand-and-phone",
      "name": "Wallet, Nightstand and Phone",
      "instructions": "It's useful to remind ourselves of our higher goals and priorities by displaying them where we will notice them. Pick three cards from any category.\n\n1. **Wallet**: Keep one card in your wallet or purse \u2014 a goal you wish to always keep at the forefront of your mind (perhaps from the SELF, LOVE, FAMILY or MEANING categories). By carrying it with you everywhere, it becomes a physical reminder of what truly matters.\n\n2. **Nightstand**: Leave one card on your bedside table \u2014 a goal you wish to be reminded of at the beginning or end of each day, that can be worked on first thing in the morning or just before sleep (perhaps from the SELF, BODY or MOOD category).\n\n3. **Phone**: Take a photo of one priority and set it as your phone's backdrop. You'll be regularly nudged towards your true aspiration.",
      "groups": [
        "Wallet",
        "Nightstand",
        "Phone"
      ]
    }
  ]
}